Defendant Junius S Moore in court with attorney Patrick T. Earle.  Defendant Junius S Moore in custody.  David Robles appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk: dds.

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements made by State, defense, and defendant. 
 
AS TO COUNT 5:  The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 7 YEARS, CONSECUTIVE to any other time being served with credit for 259 days served. The INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 3 YEARS.  The MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION IS 4 YEARS.

The defendant IS eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and the Substance Abuse Program AFTER SERVING THE FIRST 2 YEARS OF THIS SENTENCE.

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
*Obtain AODA assessment and if necessary successfully complete follow-up treatment;
*Cooperate with random urine screens;
*No drug dealing or association with drug community (drug users/dealers or drug houses);
*Cooperate with any and all rules set forth by the probation agent;
*No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause;
*No contact with victim Felicia M.;
*Obtain/maintain full time employment or full time school and part time employment;
*Obtain High school diploma, GED or HSED;
*Participate in Anger management program;
*Participate in Cognitive thinking program;
*Pay all supervision fees;
*Provide DNA sample- pay surcharge;
*Pay all applicable mandatory surcharges, fees, assessments, and costs; 

State in compliance with victim rights legislation.  The Court ordered restitution set at zero.  The Court ordered that all financial obligations be paid through collection of sums by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment.  Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes Section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession, Body armor possession, and Voting.  Appeal rights given.
